    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Small to medium-sized seabass with a robust body and attractive colouration. Dorsal fin with 11–13 spines and 15–17 rays. Three large spines on the operculum, frontal nostrils with broad flap. Body pale yellow-brown with small orange spots and scattered dark-brown blotches. Pectoral and pelvic fins yellowish, anal and tail fin with more grey and a narrow white edge.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_10212",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Reaches up 35 cm total length.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_10213",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to Southern Africa, with reports from Namibia. &nbsp;</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> False Bay to Durban, 1–25 m depth.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_10214",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Adults are solitary and sedentary and found on shallow rocky reefs. Several observations from False Bay but not commonly seen. Very little known about its biology.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_10215",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Generalist predator feeding on smaller bottom-dwelling invertebrates, such as crustaceans, as well as fish.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_10216",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Little is known about reproduction. Pelagic larvae metamorphose at 9 mm length into benthic juveniles.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_10217",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Unlikely to be confused as the colouration with small orange spots is distinctive. The only other seabass in the kelp forest, the Yellowbellied Rockcod <i>Epinephelus marginatus</i>, is much larger. Could at first glance perhaps be confused with members in the klipfish group, in particular the very rare and large Robust klipfish <i>Clinus robustus </i>that grows to a similar size. However, klipfishes have a more elongated body shape and the coloration of the Robust klipfish is different.</p><p>Another species, the Whiteblotch koester, occurs only on the east coast of South Africa.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_10218",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa (Fifth edition). Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 282).<br><br>Heemstra, P & Heemstra, E (2004). Coastal Fishes of South Africa. NISC, Grahamstown. (p. 159).<br><br>Heemstra, P, Heemstra, E, Ebert, D, Holleman, W & Randall, J (2022). Coastal Fishes of the Western Indian Ocean. National Research Foundation & South African Institute for Aquatic Biodiversity, South Africa. Volume 4 (p. 89).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_10219",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
    ],
